    74	---
    75	
    76	## 3. Workforce Personas vs. Assistant Traits/Persona
    77	
    78	### They are different things solving different problems
    79	
    80	**Workforce personas** are runtime execution profiles. A persona defines:
    81	- a system prompt
    82	- a model
    83	- a harness (Claude, Codex, OpenCode)
    84	- harness settings
    85	- optional skills
    86	- service tiers (`best`, `best-value`, `minimum`)
    87	
    88	Personas answer: **"What runtime configuration should this agent use to execute a task?"**
    89	
    90	A routing profile selects which persona tier to use per intent. The workload-router resolves `intent → persona + tier → concrete runtime config`.
    91	
    92	**Assistant traits** are identity and behavioral characteristics. Traits would define:
    93	- voice and communication style
    94	- domain vocabulary and framing
    95	- behavioral defaults (proactivity level, formality, risk tolerance)
    96	- formatting preferences per surface
    97	- personality continuity across sessions
    98	
    99	Traits answer: **"How should this assistant present itself and behave across interactions?"**
   100	
   101	### Relationship without collapse
   102	
   103	```
   104	workforce persona (runtime config)     assistant traits (identity + behavior)
   105	         │                                        │
   106	         ▼                                        ▼
   107	  ┌─────────────┐                        ┌──────────────┐
   108	  │ model        │                        │ voice         │
   109	  │ harness      │                        │ style         │
   110	  │ system prompt│◄── prompt may embed ───│ vocabulary    │
   111	  │ tier policy  │    trait values         │ proactivity   │
   112	  │ skills       │                        │ risk posture  │
   113	  └─────────────┘                        └──────────────┘
   114	```
   115	
   116	- A workforce persona's `systemPrompt` may **embed** trait values (e.g., "You are Sage, a knowledge-focused assistant who speaks concisely"), but the prompt itself is a persona concern — it is the execution-time artifact.
   117	- Traits are the **source data** that multiple prompts, formatters, and behavioral policies can read from.
   118	- A single assistant identity (e.g., "Sage") may be served by multiple workforce personas at different tiers, but the traits remain constant across all tiers.
   119	- Products compose traits into personas, not the other way around.
   120	
   121	### Integration points
   122	
   123	| Concern | Owner | Consumes traits? |
   124	| --- | --- | --- |
   125	| Persona resolution (`resolvePersona`) | Workforce workload-router | No — personas are self-contained runtime configs. Products may inject trait values into prompt templates before passing to the persona. |
   126	| Routing mode selection (`router.decide()`) | `@relay-assistant/routing` | No — routing is about depth/latency/cost, not identity. |
   127	| Surface formatting (`formatHook`) | `@relay-assistant/surfaces` | Yes — a format hook may read traits to adjust voice, block style, or formality per surface. |
   128	| Session continuity | `@relay-assistant/sessions` | No — sessions track state, not identity. |
   129	| Coordination synthesis | `@relay-assistant/coordination` | Yes — a synthesizer may read traits to maintain consistent voice when merging specialist outputs. |
   130	| Proactive behavior (future) | `@relay-assistant/proactive` | Yes — traits like proactivity level and risk posture inform watch rules and follow-up thresholds. |
   131	
   132	### What this means for implementations
   133	
   134	Products should:
   135	1. Define traits as a data object (not a package import in v1 — this is product-owned for now)
   136	2. Pass trait values into persona prompts, format hooks, and synthesizer configs as needed
   137	3. Not expect the assistant SDK to enforce trait consistency — that is the product's responsibility until a traits package exists
   138	
   139	---
   140	
   141	## 4. Where a Traits Layer Should Live
   142	
   143	### Proposed package: `@relay-assistant/traits`
   144	
   145	**Position in the package map:**
   146	
   147	| Package | Purpose |
   148	| --- | --- |
   149	| `@relay-assistant/core` | Assistant definition, lifecycle, runtime composition |
   150	| **`@relay-assistant/traits`** | **Assistant identity traits: voice, style, vocabulary, behavioral defaults, surface formatting preferences** |
   151	| `@relay-assistant/memory` | Memory scopes, stores, retrieval, promotion |
   152	| `@relay-assistant/sessions` | Session identity, lifecycle, surface attachment |
   153	| `@relay-assistant/surfaces` | Surface abstractions, normalization, fanout |
   154	| `@relay-assistant/coordination` | Specialist orchestration, synthesis |
   155	| `@relay-assistant/connectivity` | Inter-agent signaling, convergence |
   156	| `@relay-assistant/routing` | Depth/latency/cost mode selection |
   157	| `@relay-assistant/proactive` | Follow-ups, watchers, schedulers |
   158	| `@relay-assistant/policy` | Approvals, safeguards, audit |
   159	
   160	### Package scope
   161	
   162	`@relay-assistant/traits` should own:
   163	
   164	- `AssistantTraits` type definition (voice, style, vocabulary, proactivity level, risk posture, formality, domain framing)
   165	- `SurfaceFormattingTraits` type definition (per-surface-type formatting preferences that inform format hooks)
   166	- `TraitsProvider` interface — a read-only accessor that packages can consume without hard-depending on traits
   167	- `createTraitsProvider(traits: AssistantTraits)` factory
   168	- Validation that trait values are within acceptable ranges/enums
   169	
   170	`@relay-assistant/traits` must NOT own:
   171	
   172	- Persona definitions — those stay in workforce
   173	- System prompts — those are persona artifacts, not traits
   174	- Product-specific behavioral logic — stays in product repos
   175	- Model selection or routing — stays in `routing`
   176	- Memory or session state — stays in those packages
   177	
   178	### Dependency direction
   179	
   180	```
   181	traits ← core (optional: definition may reference a TraitsProvider)
   182	traits ← surfaces (optional: format hooks may consume traits)
   183	traits ← coordination (optional: synthesizer may consume traits)
   184	traits ← proactive (optional: watch rules may consume traits)
   185	```
   186	
   187	Traits has **zero upstream dependencies** on other SDK packages. It is a leaf data package.
   188	
   189	### Integration with `AssistantDefinition`
   190	
   191	The current `AssistantDefinition` has `id`, `name`, `description?`. When traits ships:
   192	
   193	```typescript
   194	export interface AssistantDefinition {
   195	  id: string;
   196	  name: string;
   197	  description?: string;
   198	  traits?: TraitsProvider;  // NEW — optional, from @relay-assistant/traits
   199	  capabilities: Record<string, CapabilityHandler>;
   200	  hooks?: AssistantHooks;
   201	  constraints?: RuntimeConstraints;
   202	}
   203	```
   204	
   205	The `traits?` field is optional so existing consumers are unaffected. Products that want trait-driven formatting, synthesis, or proactive behavior wire a `TraitsProvider` at definition time. Packages that consume traits access it via `runtime.definition.traits`.
   206	
   207	### Timeline
   208	
   209	- **v1 (now):** No traits package. Products define traits as local data objects. This is fine for the current adoption phase.
   210	- **v1.1 (with memory):** Consider traits spec alongside memory. Memory and traits often interact (e.g., "remember that this user prefers informal voice" is a memory-stored trait override).
   211	- **v1.2 (with proactive + coordination maturity):** Traits package implementation. By this point, multiple products will have local trait patterns worth extracting.
   212	
   213	### Extraction signal
   214	
   215	The same rule that governs all SDK extraction applies: if a capability is reusable across multiple assistants with only configuration changes, it belongs here. When Sage, MSD, and NightCTO all have local trait objects with overlapping field shapes, the extraction is justified.
